            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-09-28T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-09-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="199" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d199">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Department of State Atomic Energy Files</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chairman of the Joint Congressional Committee on Atomic
                        Energy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">McMahon</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to President <persName type="to">Truman</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d199fn1">Senator McMahon addressed a separate letter to
                        President Truman on September 28 dealing with the international control of
                        atomic energy in light of the atomic explosion in the Soviet Union; for
                        text, see <ref target="#pg_179">p. 179</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-09-28">September 28,
                            1949</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. President</hi>: On July 14, 1949, I wrote letters
                    to Secretary of Defense Johnson and to the Atomic Energy Commission (copy <pb facs="0574" n="544" xml:id="pg_544"/> enclosed, classified Top Secret),<note n="2" xml:id="d199fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_482">p. 482</ref>.</note>
                    suggesting that production requirements in the field of atomic energy be
                    increased.</p>
                <p>Of course, I now adhere even more firmly to the views expressed in the letter of
                    July 14, and am passing it on in the hope that you may find it helpful in
                    considering whether or not a supplemental budget request should be forwarded to
                    the present Congress. I particularly call your attention to the fact that since
                    1945 only about one-thirtieth (1/30) of our expenditures directly for national
                    defense have been devoted to development of atomic energy.</p>
                <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Brien McMahon</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
